	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Prospects for the EU dairy sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 May 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In the dairy sector the latest EC review of the prospects for EU agricultural markets and incomes notes that short-term prospects are dominated by the scale of the financial and economic crisis. A substantial fall in producer prices of milk in 2009 is expected, following a ‘pronounced decline in the prices of dairy products’. In the face of these market trends EU milk production is expected to contract. Under-utilisation of allocated production quotas is expected to increase up to 2010. In the medium term a recovery in production is projected, although still at below-quota levels. In this context, ‘the abolition of milk quotas in 2015/16 is not projected to have a significant impact on milk production and milk price’. </p><p>Higher-value dairy products are expected to be more severely affected by the economic down-turn. This being noted, EU cheese production is expected to continue with uninterrupted increase in the coming period, with production in 2015 being 10.6% above the level of production in 2007. EU consumption of cheese is also projected to increase steadily, although at a slightly slower rate in 2009, as a result of the economic crisis. Exports are foreseen to expand slightly up to 2014, following a short-term decline. However ‘the growth in domestic consumption would absorb most of the increase in cheese production, leading to a steady drop in exports in the last years of the projection period’. Exports in 2015 are thus projected to be 11.9% less than in 2007. Nevertheless EU cheese exports will still be over 500,000 tonnes throughout the period.</p><p><b>EU: Cheese (thousand tonnes) </b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
