<td width="101" valign="top">  2015
  </td><td width="144" valign="top">  787
  </td><td width="162" valign="top">  729
  </td><td width="126" valign="top">  8
  </td><td width="126" valign="top">  101
  </td><td width="126" valign="top">  +93
  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>According to an EC commodity market update, there has been a continued decline in international dairy prices, with butter, cheese, skimmed-milk and whole-milk powder declining 20%, 22%, 4% and 2.6% respectively since December 2008. This leaves butter, cheese, skimmed-milk powder and whole-milk powder 55%, 55%, 66% and 63% respectively below their 2007 peak levels. International skimmed-milk powder prices are now as low as they were in 2003. It is argued that policy measures such as intervention purchases should help halt the current price declines in the EU, with the EC hoping that dairy prices are now bottoming out. However major uncertainties have been generated by the depth of the financial and associated economic crisis, with fears growing that consumers could substitute dairy products with cheaper alternatives. The current difficulties in the EU dairy sector are in distinct contrast to the favourable market situation in 2006 and 2007 which ‘allowed the EU to clear all public stocks of skimmed-milk powder and butter’ and progressively reduce and halt all support measures specifically targeting dairy products.</p><p>Against the background of these price trends and with EU dairy-sector intervention buying on the increase, a number of EU member states including Germany have ‘called upon the European Council to re-open the dairy chapter of the CAP health check, notably to postpone the quota expansion’. Commissioner Fischer Boel has so far refused such a measure, arguing that this would mislead farmers as to the overall policy direction. According to the USDA <i>GAIN</i> report, the Commissioner further argued that the quota increase ‘would not necessarily raise overall production’, and hence would have little impact on the market balance, and pointed out that farmers were ‘now basing their production decisions on market prices and cost structures rather than quota levels’. The Commissioner’s refusal to defer the quota increase was supported by the Dutch, Swedish, Danish, Spanish and UK governments who ‘defended the quota increase on the presumption that other exporting countries were waiting to take EU market shares in the world market if the EU reduced its exports’.</p><p>Commissioner Fischer Boel pointed out that maintaining the proposed quota expansion did not mean that the EU was doing nothing to address the problems in the dairy sector. Addressing the European Parliament’s Agriculture and Rural Development Committee, she noted five areas of EU support:</p><p>· direct aid payments worth €5 billion a year, ‘which dairy farmers receive whatever the weather’;</p><p>· the provision since January 2009 of export refunds and support for private storage;</p><p>· intervention buying, which is ‘in full swing’;</p><p>· the economic recovery package which will ‘provide extra money to help the dairy sector to restructure’;</p><p>· member states’ support through state aid under the ‘de-minimis’ rules, by export credit guarantees or through article 68 measures.</p><p>The Commissioner argued that there were now signs that these policy measures were having an effect, with dairy prices stabilising. She concluded that the ‘current policy response will be strong enough to cushion farmers against the worst of the market crisis – but not so strong that we insulate them from market signals and harm their long-term interests’.</p>
		
		
